name: Printer, AltaLink B8045/55 multi-functional device (MFD)
description:
This systems process represents the life cycle of a Xerox AltaLink B8045 or B8055 product system under average operating conditions. The data are extracted from a full cradle-to-grave life cycle of the AltaLink B8000 Series devices compiled and verified internally by Xerox Corporation LCA and Environmental, Health, Safety, & Sustainability practitioners. . These devices are multifunctional devices (MFD) capable of black and white laser printing, copy, scan, and fax. The functional unit is a simplex job of 1000 pages or a duplex job of 750 pages. The study was performed as a carbon footprint indented to meet optional EPEAT environmental performance criteria for imaging equipment. 

The system boundary includes four main life cycle stages: material and manufacturing, transportation, use, and end-of-life. The material and manufacturing stage includes the extraction of raw material inputs and the processes required to manufacture the materials into its desired state for product assembly. The packaging is treated as part of the product system. The transportation phase captures the transport of the multifunction printer from the manufacturing sites to the regions of use. The use phase of this life cycle assessment includes the energy consumption, paper consumption, toner cartridge consumption, print cartridge consumption, and the associated production, transportation, and disposal of each of these three reference consumables. Service and maintenance are excluded from this study because spare parts are not expected to be needed during the defined 5-year lifespan of the product system. Remanufacturing activities for the product and consumables are excluded because most of the product is recyclable. Product specific data for the recyclability of the AltaLink B8000 series devices are based on the anticipated take back and recycling scenario.

processDocumentation.timeDescription: This system process is representative of the device life cycle for normal operating conditions from 2013 to 2018. The entire lifetime of the product according to the PCR is assumed to be 5 years for all products within the scope of the rule. In order to account for the accurate portion of the product lifetime, the lifetime reference flows for all AltaLink B8000 series devices are scaled according to the functional unit (i.e., 1,200,000 pages of simplex jobs per 5 years). In order to make these calculations it was assumed that there are 365.25 days or 52.18 weeks in a year. In this lifetime (i.e., 5 years), 126.55 kg of the multifunctional printing device (one printer including packaging), 12.0 kg toner cartridge (24.0 cartridges), and 16.902 kg xerographic print cartridge (6.0 cartridges) are required.
processDocumentation.technologyDescription:
This process represents the cradle-to-grave life cycle of a printer, AltaLink B8045/55 multi-functional device (MFD); simplex job 1000 pages under normal operating conditions for North America from 2013 to 2018. The system boundary includes four main life cycle stages: material and manufacturing, transportation, use, and end-of-life. The material and manufacturing stage includes the extraction of raw material inputs and the processes required to manufacture the materials into its desired state for product assembly. The packaging is treated as part of the product system. The transportation phase captures the transport of the multifunction printer from the manufacturing sites to the regions of use. The use phase of this life cycle assessment includes the energy consumption, paper consumption, toner cartridge consumption, print cartridge consumption, and the associated production, transportation, and disposal of each of these three reference consumables. Service and maintenance are excluded from this study because spare parts are not expected to be needed during the defined 5-year lifespan of the product system. Remanufacturing activities for the product and consumables are excluded because most of the product is recyclable. Product specific data for the recyclability of the AltaLink B8000 series devices are based on the anticipated take back and recycling scenario.

The AltaLink B8000 series devices are typically purchased by businesses who anticipate a volume of print, copy, scan, and/or fax and that is higher than what a small desktop device can meet. These devices are typically faster, have higher consumable yield, are more reliable and have a longer life span than smaller desktop devices. The typical use of the devices is for large volume print jobs and/or a high quantity of jobs. In some cases, multiple small desktop printers, copiers, scanners and/or fax machines are removed from a customer location and replaced with a single larger MFD, such as an AltaLink B8000 series device, to consolidate and efficiently update the print fleet. Primary business industries that notably require the functionality of AltaLink B8000 series devices in their offices include higher education, healthcare and finance.

The AltaLink B8045 and B8055 are two model configurations in the AltaLink B8000 Series with the same base technology and optional attachments, but different specifications. These two models have the same image output terminal (IOT), which houses the engine and main printing capabilities, in addition to a catch tray. The AltaLink B8055 has higher system specifications than the AltaLink B8045. However, both products have the same typical energy consumption and average monthly print volume, making the modeling and results of both systems equal. The B8045 model has simplex speeds of 45, 36, and 31 ppm for 8.5x11 inch/A4, 8.5x13 to 8.5x14 inch/A4-B4, and 11x17 inch/A3 sheet sizes, respectively. The B8055 model has simplex speeds of 55, 36, and 31 ppm for 8.5x11 inch/A4, 8.5x13 to 8.5x14 inch/A4-B4, and 11x17 inch/A3 sheet sizes, respectively. The maximum duplex speed for the 8.5x11 inch/A4 sheet size is 45 ppm/2-sided 22.5 spm, and 55 ppm/2-sided 32.5 spm for the B8045 and B8055 devices, respectively. The maximum monthly duty cycle is 175,000 and 200,000 pages for the B8045 and B8055 devices, respectively. The toner type is emulsion aggregate (EA) [chemical] and the maximum print resolution is 1200x1200 dpi.
processDocumentation.dataCollectionDescription: All primary data were collected from 2013 to 2014. Secondary data were compiled from ecoinvent 2013-2018 (Xerox Corporation 2018).
processDocumentation.completenessDescription:
TREATMENT OF MISSING ENVIRONMENTAL & TECHNOSPHERE DATA
The total of all excluded flows are less than 5% of mass, energy, or environmental impacts in any criteria. Any data gaps are filled by documented conservative assumptions with average or generic data. If there is insufficient data to input or fill gaps, less than 2% renewable and non-renewable energy usage and less than 2% total mass is viable to exclude. The 5% cut-off criteria also applied to the sum of excluded environmental impacts per life cycle stage. Spread across various assemblies of the AltaLink B8045/55, 1.3 kg of weight has unknown material and manufacturing associations, which is 1% of the total. According to the data collected, the total weight of the B8045/B8055 without packaging is 126.8 kg, while the actual weight of the printer and finisher according to the system specifications is 126.55 kg. This very slight difference in weight could be due to incorrect supplier declarations, duplicated entries in instances where a part is represented by both a Xerox part number and a vendor part number, or lack of clarity in the inclusion or exclusion of cartridge components. This exclusion falls well under the 2% cut-off criteria for mass exclusion. It is not expected that these assemblies would have materials that significantly affect emission to air, water, or soil so this exclusion meets all cut-off criteria. The production of toner only includes the production of the principle particles for Xerox Emulsion Aggregate (EA) toner, but any further manufacturing processes are difficult to obtain so are not included. Most printer manufacturers have a chemical toner process, and processes vary among them due to intellectual property and patenting. Final manufacturing processes were not obtained because of this proprietary nature of the information and because the exclusion falls well within the cut-off criteria.

MASS BALANCE
The mass imbalance for this unit process is < 0.1%.
processDocumentation.dataSelectionDescription: The AltaLink B8000 series devices are Xerox Corporation products with distribution to North America and Europe. However, because the logistical transport route to North America is longer than to Europe, the route analyzed in this study is that to a final distribution center in North America. Because the goal of this study is intended to meet the U.S. based EPEAT criteria, the analysis of transport to and use in the U.S. aligns with the goal and scope. Two main transportation routes occur through North America: 30% to the Cerritos, California warehouse and 70% to the Groveport, Ohio warehouse. In this study, the transport to Groveport, Ohio is considered because it is the majority and longest route.
processDocumentation.reviewDetails: The data have only undergone internal review. Pending the critical review, Xerox intends to be able to declare the AltaLink B8045 and B8055 products as EPEAT Gold certified.
processDocumentation.dataTreatmentDescription: In an effort to assess this product family by common industry terms the UL Environment product category rules (PCR) for printers and multi-function printing units is followed. The AltaLink B8045 and B8055 fall into the scope of the PCR as multifunction devices that do not use continuous form paper or use paper sizes larger than A3 or have a speed greater than 75 ppm. The PRC defines life cycle assessment criteria including systems boundaries, functional unit, product lifetime, energy consumption, paper and media consumption (optional), consumable use, maintenance stage, transportation, background data, cut-off criteria, and allocation criteria. According to the PCR, the functional unit is defined as a 1000 page simplex job. According to the PCR, the inclusion of ‘Paper and Media Consumption’ is optional; however, it was included in this LCA in order to create the most complete study as possible. Also according to the PCR, the manufacturing, transportation, and disposal of all consumables will be reflected in the use phase. The use phase typical energy consumption (TEC) method for the most current version (Version 2.0 – 2014) of the ENERGY STAR Imaging Equipment (IE) specification was used to determine a TEC for each device. The typical electricity consumption of either the AltaLink B8045 or B8055 devices is 4.8 kWh/week. Since the AltaLink B8000 series devices only have monochrome capabilities there is no color consumable considered. The number of toner cartridges consumed per 1000 page functional unit is 0.02 cartridges. The AltaLink B8000 series are unique devices because they consume both print xerography cartridge and toner cartridge consumables. The toner cartridge is mainly a bottle assembly containing the actual toner marking material. The print xerography cartridge contains the xerographic drums, developer module, including dual auger ring, toner dispense, toner concentration sensor, development roll, trim bar, and developer material. The developer material at the beginning of its life contains 25 grams toner and 250 grams carrier beads. The xerography print cartridge has a stated life of 200,000 prints. The entire lifetime of the product according to the PCR is assumed to be 5 years for all products within the scope of the rule. In order to account for the accurate portion of the product lifetime, the lifetime reference flows for all AltaLink B8000 series devices are scaled according to the functional unit. The portion of printer consumed by the function unit is determined by first scaling the total number of simplex jobs, energy consumption, paper consumption, and toner cartridge consumption. In order to make these calculations it was assumed that there are 365.25 days or 52.18 weeks in a year.

processDocumentation.modelingConstantsDescription: Since each reference flow is scaled based on each devices unique lifetime simplex job pages and 1000 page functional unit simplex job the scaling factor is slightly different for each device in the AltaLink B8000 series. The scaling factor for the B8045/B8055 is 0.000833, which indicates that 0.000833 of 1 AltaLink 8045/8055 is consumed by the 1000 page simplex job functional unit. This allocation was completed for each device including in this study and was completed in terms of the total weight of the printer system and the toner cartridge assembly. The portion of printer consumed by the function unit is determined by first scaling the total number of simplex jobs, energy consumption, paper consumption, and toner cartridge consumption The analysis of the printer and consumable end-of-life is based off of the anticipated take back and recycling scenario.
processDocumentation.samplingDescription:
BOUNDARY CONDITIONS
The system boundary includes four main life cycle stages: material and manufacturing, transportation, use, and end-of-life. The material and manufacturing stage includes the extraction of raw material inputs and the processes required to manufacture the materials into its desired state for product assembly. Raw material extraction and production is assumed to be in the same region as the final product manufacturing. Data are not known for materials pre-processing, therefore only the main material processes are used for material processing, such as injection molding for plastics. Pre-processes such as removing flashes are not specifically known or dealt with and are assumed to be accounted for in other manufacturing requirements analyzed.
The packaging is treated as part of the product system. The B8045/B8055 catch tray is the most relevant configuration for these models and the target population and so is the only attachment included in the scope of this study. No other attachments are evaluated in this study because Xerox’s EPEAT declaration targets general service administrator (GSA) customers who generally purchase the product with the aforementioned attachment. The devices also have optional accessories of high capacity feeder (HCF), envelope tray, envelope tray kit, office finisher, office finisher with booklet maker, hole punch for office finisher, high volume finisher, high volume finisher with booklet maker, post process inserter, convenience stapler, smart card enablement kit, walk up fax, Wi-Fi direct with optional Xerox ® USB wireless adapter, McAfee ® Integrity control enablement kit, XPS print option kit, and keyboard kit. However, the typical customer will only purchase the base model along with the catch tray. Laser printers typically include replaceable parts such as photoconductors, transfer rollers, fuser rollers, and supplies such as waste toner bottles. However, given the functional unit calculations, these parts are not expected to be replaced in the defined life span of the device and therefore not included in this assessment. 

The transportation phase captures the transport of the multifunction printer from the manufacturing sites to the regions of use. In this study, this transport includes that from the final manufacturing site in Senai, Malaysia to the final distribution center in North America. It is assumed that raw materials are sourced from Asia where the market for most raw materials is most economical; therefore, transportation from raw material production plant to manufacturing site is negligible. 

The use phase of this life cycle assessment includes the energy consumption, paper consumption, toner cartridge consumption, print cartridge consumption, and the associated production, transportation, and disposal of each of these three reference consumables. An average U.S. electrical production mix is used to represent the use phase. Service and maintenance are excluded from this study because spare parts are not expected to be needed during the defined 5-year lifespan of the product system (i.e., the highest replacement rate parts are expected to be replaced after 3 million prints, which occurs well after the 5-year lifetime). 

Remanufacturing activities for the product and consumables are excluded because most of the product is recyclable. Product specific data are available for the recyclability. The AltaLink B8000 series devices are newly launched products in the market, so no actual products have reached their end of life. Therefore, the analysis of the printer and consumable end-of-life is based off on the anticipated take back and recycling scenario.

DATA COLLECTION
The scope of this LCA study is a carbon footprint as defined according to the UL Environment product category rules (PCR) on printers and multifunctional devices. This specific PCR was chosen for this study because it was developed recently according to ISO 14025 and it was harmonized with other existing PCRs. The PRC defines life cycle assessment criteria including systems boundaries, functional unit, product lifetime, energy consumption, paper and media consumption (optional), consumable use, maintenance stage, transportation, background data, cut-off criteria, and allocation criteria. According to the PCR, the inclusion of ‘Paper and Media Consumption’ is optional; however, it was included in this LCA in order to create the most complete study as possible. The use phase typical energy consumption (TEC) method for the most current version (Version 2.0 – 2014) of the ENERGY STAR Imaging Equipment (IE) specification was used to determine a TEC for each device. These typical energy consumption measurements were determined in an independent testing lab and gathered from the associate product manager of the AltaLink B8000 series devices. According to the PCR, the Daily Pages Printed should be determined based off on the TEC test procedure job table, which determines the number of images per day as a function of the device speed. However, the average monthly print volume for the AltaLink B8000 series devices is known from the Xerox product specifications and therefore does not need to be estimated as a function of device speed. 

The entire lifetime of the product according to the PCR is assumed to be 5 years for all products within the scope of the rule. In order to account for the accurate portion of the product lifetime, the lifetime reference flows for all AltaLink B8000 series devices are scaled according to the functional unit. The scaled reference flows are those used to accurately model the system because these represent the portion of the product system consumed during the defined 1000 page simplex job functional unit. The portion of printer consumed by the function unit is determined by first scaling the total number of simplex jobs, energy consumption, paper consumption, and toner cartridge consumption.

UNCERTAINTY ESTIMATION
Uncertainty was estimated based on engineering judgment.

processDocumentation.intendedApplication:
The study assesses the global warming potential impacts associated with the materials and manufacture, transportation, use, and end-of-life of the multifunctional device. Paper consumption during the use phase contributes the most to the greenhouse gas emissions of the life cycle for all AltaLink B8000 devices, followed by the materials and manufacturing, transportation, and end-of-life. 

This LCA was conducted from cradle-to-grave according to the requirements of the ISO 14067 standard. The goal of this study is to determine the cradle-to-grave greenhouse gas emissions (GHG) associated with the Xerox AltaLink B8045 and B8055 multifunctional devices (MFDs). The results of the assessment are intended to meet optional Electronic Product Environmental Assessment Tool (EPEAT) environmental performance criteria for imaging equipment. The optional criteria that are intended to be met through the completion of this assessment are outlined in the IEEE Standard for Environmental Assessment of Imaging Equipment and listed as criteria 4.5.2.1 (Optional – Product specific greenhouse gas emissions – life-cycle assessment) and 4.5.2.2 (Optional – Product specific greenhouse gas emissions – third-party verification or making LCA assessment publicly available).

SITUATION C2 -- ACCOUNTING
Same as in SITUATION C1 except LCA studies categorized under Goal Situation C2 do NOT consider existing benefits outside the analyzed system such as recycling. Situation C1 description - The intended application for this process is for accounting purposes as described in Goal Situation C1 from the ILCD Handbook's Detailed Guidance. LCA studies with this intended application offer "purely descriptive documentation of the system under analysis (e.g., a product, sector or country), without being interested in any potential consequences on other parts of the economy.” The studies categorized under Goal Situation C1 do consider existing benefits outside the analyzed system such as recycling.
processDocumentation.projectDescription: This LCA was conducted from cradle-to-grave according to the requirements of the ISO 14067 standard. The results of the assessment are intended to meet optional Electronic Product Environmental Assessment Tool (EPEAT) environmental performance criteria for imaging equipment. The optional criteria that are intended to be met through the completion of this assessment are outlined in the IEEE Standard for Environmental Assessment of Imaging Equipment and listed as criteria 4.5.2.1 and 4.5.2.2.; this study is not intended to make comparative assertions about products within the B8000 series of devices.
processDocumentation.geographyDescription: This process is representative of normal device operating conditions in North America. Production data are from manufacturing sites in Senai, Malaysia. Most raw materials are assumed to be sourced from Asia where the market is most economical. Distribution data are representative of North American distribution centers. The average US electrical production mix is used to represent use phase electricity consumption. The printer cartridge, including the toner, is manufacturing in the same location as the printer device in Senai, Malaysia. However, service and maintenance are excluded from this study because spare parts are not expected to be needed during the defined 5-year lifespan of the product system.
